[1] Peru (Loreto)
Date: Wed 20 Jul 2011
Source: La Region [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
http://diariolaregion.com/web/2011/07/20/direccion-regional-de-salud-alerta-sobre-brote-de-hantavirus-en-loreto/


In a press conference, the Loreto Government Regional Health
Directorate provided information related to measures to follow for
prevention of the transmission of hantavirus infection, which recently
took the life of a victim in our city [Loreto], the 1st which has
occurred in Peru. On 8 Jul [2011], a 29 year old a woman died in the
EsSalud Hospital, and the case was confirmed as a hantavirus
[infection] by tests done in the National Institute of Health.

Hantaviruses are found in some rodent species around the world. These
viruses are transmitted when infected rodents contaminate, with their
feces and urine, houses and buildings closed for a long time. People
who clean, dust, or sweep without protection become infected when they
breathe dust with feces or urine, with some [individuals] later
developing severe respiratory disease with intense coughing and
difficulty in breathing, which requires intensive care management.

Because of this, the Regional Health Directorate is carrying out the
necessary investigations with the help of professionals from the
General Directorate of Epidemiology and the National Institute of
Health to determine if this is an isolated case that was infected
accidentally.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The hantavirus involved in this case is not specified. A hantavirus
that cause HPS (hantavirus pulmonary syndrome) that is found in the
Amazon Basin is Araraquara and its rodent host is (_Necromys (Bolomys)
benefactus_).

A HealthMap ProMED-mail map showing the location of Iquitos in Loreto
department, Peru can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/0lV7. -
Mod. TY]

******
[2] Peru (Loreto)
Date: Tue 19 Jul 2011
From: Juan Carlos Celis Salinas <charapa3@yahoo.com> [edited]


[This is the same case as the one above, but with some additional
details. - Mod.TY]

The 1st case of hantavirus pulmonary syndrome (HPS) has been
confirmed (ELISA and PCR) in the Peruvian [Amazon], Iquitos, [Loreto
region] Peru. Sadly, the case was fatal, involving a 29 year old woman
who worked as a nature tourist guide near Iquitos city. After a 20 day
illness, she developed a clinical picture of serious respiratory
insufficiency in the Hospital III Iquitos-EsSalud. The pulmonary
disease specialist, Percy Sinti, was alert to the possibility of HPS,
and arranged for samples to be taken that were sent to the National
Institute of Health and the Center for Tropical Diseases Research of
the US Navy based in Iquitos, which confirmed the physician's
suspicions.

The patient died in the intensive care unit on 8 Jul 2011. Although
reports of serological evidence of hantavirus [infection], there has
never been a confirmed case in Peru. Following the confirmation,
epidemiological investigations of contacts and probable sites of
infection and the search for wild rodents, probable virus reservoir
hosts, have been initiated.

--
Dr Juan Carlos Celis Salinas
Infectious Diseases Physician
Hospital Regional de Loreto, Iquitos, Peru
<charapa3@yahoo.com>

[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Celis Salinas for sending this report. -
Mod.TY]

