[3] Paraguay (Presidente Hayes)
Date: Sat 16 Jul 2011
Source: La Nacion [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.lanacion.com.py/articulo.php?hay-alerta-por-nueve-casos-de-hantavirus-en-zona-d&edicion=2&sec=10&art=30681


The Ministry of Public Health has confirmed 9 hantavirus [infection]
cases in the country this year [2011]. Of this number of infected
individuals, 2 people are currently admitted to the Central Hospital
of the Institute of Social Services (IPS), while the deaths of another
2 people are currently under investigation. The affected
[hospitalized] individuals are residents of Villa Hayes Chaco,
Presidente Hayes department [state of province equivalent], from the
same area as the cases who died of this disease, according to a press
conference yesterday [15 Jul 2011] at the IPS.

According to the most recent report from the Office of Health
Surveillance, Ministry of Health, so far this year [2011] there have
been 9 reported cases of the disease, whereas in 2009 there were 3
reported cases, and in 2010, one infected individual, the report
indicated.

Dr Ana Finandro of the epidemiology service, stated that the
hospitalized patients are from Villa Hayes, where another 2 people
died apparently from the same cause, according to symptoms that they
presented with. She said that the results of tests done on the victims
are awaited.

In 2008, in the Boqueron department, there was a hantavirus epidemic
and the year ended with about 30 cases and 4 deaths. At that time, the
health authorities attributed the outbreak in the Chaco area to
environmental problems from deforestation of the region, constant
fires, and land clearing that favored the urbanization of rats,
carriers of the virus that causes the disease, in the communities.

_Calomys laucha_, a rural rodent common in central Chaco areas, is
the one that transmits Laguna Negra hantavirus, according to Health
Surveillance director Dr Ivan Allende's explanation.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-ESP
<promed-esp@promedmail.org>

[In addition to Laguna Negra virus, other hantaviruses that can cause
HPS and are found in Paraguay (and their rodent hosts), from a list
kindly provided by Dr James Mills, include Bermejo (_Oligoryzomys
chacoensis_), Lechiguanas (_Oligoryzomys flavescens_), Central Plata
(_Oligoryzomys flavescens_), Anajatuba (possible HPS; _Oligoryzomys
fornesi_), Oran (__Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_), and Juquitiba
(__Oligoryzomys nigripes_).

An image of _Calomys laucha_ can be accessed at
http://www.faunaparaguay.com/Calomys%20laucha%20www.pybio.org.jpg.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map showing the location of Villa Hayes,
Presidente Hayes department, can be accessed at
http://healthmap.org/r/143g. - Mod.TY]
